Here we do a big conditional in order to conver the numbers to negative if they aren't, there's probably easier ways to do this. Why do we make our numbers negatives, well because programming sucks and negative numbers have 1 more than positives... so that means we get integer overflow if we try and convert all the negatives to positives. This might still not make sense why we do this, I encourage you to try programming the solution and you will see why it is advantageous to have all the numbers be either positive or negative ( makes defining the actual long division algorithm much more easy ), other solutions that don't do this tend to lead to worse code in my opinion that would be hard to come up with without a lot of debugging...



