# Intuition
<!-- Describe your first thoughts on how to solve this problem. -->
as we cant use multiplication & division and modulo operators , first thing that comes to mind is to maintain a variable quotient and substract divisor from dividend till it is greater or equal to it.
this will take a lot of time but it is a accepted solution
can we do it in better Time complexity ? 'yes'
rather substracting the divisor linearly we can do it exponentially that is using left shift operator(1<<1 == 2 left is used to multiply any number by 2 in binary);
it is nothing but rather substracting 3 , 6 , 9 , 12 .... we gonna substract 3 , 6 , 12 , 24 , 48 ......
**hope you like the intution give a 👍 to improve my profile**
# Approach
<!-- Describe your approach to solving the problem. -->
- maintain a variable `quotient`.
- extract the resultant sign and typecast to `long` to avoid overflows.
- while `dividend is >= divisor` left shift the divisor till it is smaller than dividend.maintain number of leftshifts.
- substract dividend with the `divisor<<shift-1` as we shifted one extra bit. add number `1<<shifts-1` to quotient(number of times divisor is multiplied).
- return corresponding values for signs
# Complexity
- Time complexity:$$O(log(n))$$
<!-- Add your time complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->

- Space complexity:$$O(1)$$
<!-- Add your space complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->

# Code
```
class Solution {
    public int divide(int dividend, int divisor) {
        long quotient = 0;
        int sign = 1;
        int max = Integer.MAX_VALUE,  min = Integer.MIN_VALUE;
        if(dividend < 0 && divisor > 0 || dividend > 0 && divisor < 0)sign = -1;
        long dd = (long)dividend , dv = (long)divisor;
        dd = Math.abs(dd);dv = Math.abs(dv);
        while(dd >= dv){
            int shift = 0;
            while(dd >= (dv<<shift))shift++;
            quotient += (long)1l<<(shift-1);
            // System.out.println(quotient+"-"+shift);
            dd -= dv<<(shift-1);
        }
        if(sign == 1){
            if(quotient > max)return max;
            return (int)quotient;
        }else{
            if((~quotient)+1 < min)return min; // ~quotient+1 = -quotient
            return (int)(~quotient)+1;
        }
    }
}
```
> we can store one bigger value in negetive numbers than positive numbers so this is an asset here to avoid using long, as question clearly says the environment can only store 32 bit integers.
- rather performing division of positive values we can do it with negative values and even quotient also can be integer.

**Note : while rightshifting the divisor check for overflow.**
