solutions.content:
To quote the website exactly, we will solve the following "challange":
> Given two integers dividend and divisor, divide two integers without using multiplication, division, and mod operator.

> Return the quotient after dividing dividend by divisor.

> The integer division should truncate toward zero, which means losing its fractional part.
> For example, truncate(8.345) = 8 and truncate(-2.7335) = -2.

> Note:
>  Assume we are dealing with an environment that could only store integers within the 32-bit signed integer range: [-2^31,  2^31 − 1].
>  For this problem, assume that your function returns 2^31 - 1 when the division result overflows.

Sounds easy enough, that is to people who studied a computer systems course.
First let's look at a few of the "best" submissions that straight up violate the rules:

1. Division operator used
```
int divide(long long dividend, long long divisor){
    if(dividend/divisor>pow(2,31)-1)
        return (pow(2,31)-1);//當結果溢位時返回2^31−1
    else
        return (dividend/divisor);//其他直接除再返回其結果(因整數的除法會直接捨棄小數，輸出整數值)
}
```

2. Impressive if ladder for sure, but the pesky division operator is still there
```
#define INT_MAX 2147483647
#define INT_MIN (-INT_MAX - 1)

int divide(int dividend, int divisor){
    printf( "%d\n%d", dividend, divisor );
    int output = 0;
    if ( ( dividend == 0 ) || ( divisor == 0 ) ) return 0;
    else if ( ( dividend <= INT_MIN ) && ( divisor < 0 ) && ( divisor != INT_MIN )  ) dividend = -INT_MAX;
    // else if ( ( dividend >= INT_MAX ) || ( dividend <= INT_MIN ) ) return 0;
    // else if ( ( divisor >= INT_MAX ) || ( divisor <= INT_MIN ) ) return 0;
    output = dividend / divisor;
    // printf("%d\n",output);
    return output;
}
```

So your software restoring division (or something similar) algorithm will compete against cheaters using
division hardware, no wonder you rank poorly.

In the end it doesn't matter, as this problem in reality is asking for an algorithm that is of no use to any programmer,
aka implementing division in software. It has a horrible number of edge cases with integer overflow, and is definitely
not of "medium" difficulty to anyone, but a hardware designer.

Let's see the (terrible and pointless) code I came up with that should fit the requirements:
```
// This function implements restoring division taking two 32-bit unsigned inputs
// and outputs a 32-bit unsigned quotient, with no overflow possible
unsigned udiv(unsigned dividend, unsigned divisor) {
    unsigned quo = 0;
    unsigned long rem = dividend;
    unsigned long div = (unsigned long) divisor << 32;

    for (int i = 0; i < 32; ++i) {
        rem <<= 1;
        if (rem >= div) {
            rem -= div;
            quo = quo << 1 | 1;
        } else {
            quo <<= 1;
        }
    }

    return quo;
}

// This function does a bunch of horrific edge case checking to
// make sure no integer overflow is possible
int divide(int dividend, int divisor) {
    int sgn = 0;

    unsigned u_dividend;
    if (dividend < 0) {
        u_dividend = -(long)dividend;
        sgn ^= 1;
    } else {
        u_dividend = dividend;
    }
    unsigned u_divisor;
    if (divisor < 0) {
        u_divisor = -(long)divisor;
        sgn ^= 1;
    } else {
        u_divisor = divisor;
    }

    unsigned u_result = udiv(u_dividend, u_divisor);

    if (sgn) {
        if (-(long) u_result < INT_MIN)
            return INT_MAX;
        return -u_result;
    } else {
        if (u_result > INT_MAX)
            return  INT_MAX;
        return u_result;
    }
}
```

To add insult to injury, LeetCode is not able to actually measure the runtime of
any reasonable fast C code, so it presents mine and the two cheaters above as
having a "0 ms" runtime, and just as good. While mine is obviously slower, it
actually does what the question is asking.

