# Intuition [Top down approach]

![image.png](https://assets.leetcode.com/users/images/a22f0c55-5dfa-4b0f-817e-c1bf24627841_1678826538.8064666.png)

<!-- Describe your first thoughts on how to solve this problem. -->

# Approach
When you are in a node, you have two things to think:
1. Is this a normal node?
2. Is this a leaf node?

If this is a normal node, we somehow need to tell it's child about the value we got so far. So, we will update the value by doing: `val*10 + node.val` And pass them into both left and right children.

If this is a leaf node, we reached a base case. We can now update the globally stored variable `total`. But we need to consider our current nodes value. That's why we will do `total+=val*10 + node.val`.
<!-- Describe your approach to solving the problem. -->

# Complexity
- Time complexity: $$O(N)$$
As we are iterating for every node.
<!-- Add your time complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->

- Space complexity: $$O(N)$$
As the recursive call will iterate for every node and the function stack will be created.
<!-- Add your space complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->

# Code
``` Java []
/**
 * Definition for a binary tree node.
 * public class TreeNode {
 *     int val;
 *     TreeNode left;
 *     TreeNode right;
 *     TreeNode() {}
 *     TreeNode(int val) { this.val = val; }
 *     TreeNode(int val, TreeNode left, TreeNode right) {
 *         this.val = val;
 *         this.left = left;
 *         this.right = right;
 *     }
 * }
 */
class Solution {
    int total = 0;
    public int sumNumbers(TreeNode root) {
        helper(root, 0);
        return total;
    }

    private void helper(TreeNode node, int val){
        // is this a leaf node..
        if(node.left == null && node.right == null){
            total+=val*10 + node.val;
            return;
        }
        if(node.left!=null){
            helper(node.left, val*10+node.val);
        }
        if(node.right!=null){
            helper(node.right, val*10+node.val);
        }
    }
}
```
